<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-chapter-title" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Continuum Approximation and Calculus in Geophysical Fluid Dynamics</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      <term>Mechanics</term> is the study of motion.
      The sub-field of <term>kinematics</term> deals with simply describing motion using position, velocity, and acceleration,
      without questioning why motion happens in the first place.
      The sub-field of <term>dynamics</term> goes further: It seeks to explain the causes of motion.
      Dynamical explanations for why motion occurs use forces and related concepts like momentum and energy within the contexts of various physical laws.
      Since dynamics deals with the causes motion, it enables us to explain how motions come to be
      and<mdash />perhaps more importantly to meteorologists<mdash />predict how they will evolve in the future.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <term>Fluid dynamics</term> applies dynamics to fluids.
      A <term>fluid</term> is a substance that cannot withstand any force directed parallel to its surface:
      This applies to liquids as well as to gases like air.
      Unlike solids,
      which<mdash />at least to a point<mdash />can resist forces applied parallel to their surfaces and return to their original shapes once the forces are removed,
      fluids cannot resist such forces and instead immediately and continuously <term>deform</term> and <term>flow</term> in response to them.
      This property causes fluids to take on the shapes of their containers rather than a preferred shape like solids.
      And because their particles are in constant random motion, gases expand to occupy the entire volume of any container!
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>Geophysical fluid dynamics</term> (<acro>GFD</acro>) applies fluid dynamics to naturally occurring fluids like atmospheres and oceans.
      Therefore, <term>atmospheric dynamics</term> is a branch of GFD.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      In this atmospheric dynamics course, we will explore the causes of
      atmospheric motion<mdash />i.e., <term>wind</term><mdash />using the principles of momentum, mass, and energy conservation.
      While their corresponding physical laws are written as mathematical formulas,
      it is the physical interpretations of these equations that give them meaning and power to explain and predict atmospheric motions.
    </p>
  </introduction>

